Chapter 2 – Literature Review

2.1 World Models in Reinforcement Learning

World models learn a generative model of environment dynamics to enable planning in latent space, addressing the intractability of exact POMDP belief maintenance. DreamerV3, a general-purpose model-based reinforcement learning algorithm, learns compact latent world models to enable efficient policy optimization via imagined rollouts in latent space. The architecture comprises three primary neural modules trained in parallel: a world model (typically an RSSM), an actor for policy learning, and a critic for value estimation.

The Recurrent State-Space Model (RSSM) is the dominant architecture, combining deterministic and stochastic paths: each timestep's hidden state consists of a deterministic RNN state h_t and a stochastic latent variable z_t. The RSSM includes state transition (h_t = f_\phi(h_{t-1}, z_{t-1}, a_{t-1})), prior dynamics (\hat{z}_t \sim p_\phi(z_t \mid h_t)), encoder posterior (z_t \sim q_\phi(z_t \mid h_t, x_t)), observation decoder, and reward predictor. The training objective is a variational ELBO decomposed into reconstruction, reward prediction, and dual KL divergences with "free-bits" clipping to prevent posterior collapse.

2.2 Multimodal Perception and Scene Graphs

Recent advances have demonstrated the effectiveness of unified scene graph representations for embodied agents. MomaGraph-R1, a 7-billion parameter vision-LLM, uses a vision-language backbone with cross-modal fusion to predict semantically rich scene graphs, achieving 71.6% benchmark accuracy and demonstrating robust transfer to real-world robotics for zero-shot planning in household environments. The architecture employs cross-modal fusion achieved by inserting visual tokens into the lower layers of a text transformer via cross-attention, yielding a unified feature space.

Equivariant graph neural networks (EGNNs) provide a principled framework for learning on three-dimensional systems where predictions must respect rotational symmetries inherent in physics. These models extend traditional message-passing GNNs and Transformers by representing node and edge features as spherical tensors that transform under irreducible representations of the rotation group SO(3). Recent work has constructed SE(3) equivariant graph neural networks that can approximate geometric quantities efficiently using equivariant local complete frames.

2.3 Information Bottleneck for Graph Representation

The Information Bottleneck (IB) principle seeks representations that maximize predictive information while compressing irrelevant details. Recent work has extended IB to graph settings: the Discrete Curvature Graph Information Bottleneck (CurvGIB) framework advances the Variational Information Bottleneck (VIB) principle for Ricci curvature optimization to learn optimal information transport patterns for specific downstream tasks. Temporal graph information bottleneck (TGIB) extends the IB principle to temporal graphs, regularizing both edges and features based on a derived tractable TGIB objective via variational approximation.

2.4 Memory-Augmented Architectures

Standard Transformers suffer quadratic attention cost and context truncation, leading to catastrophic forgetting over long horizons. Memory-augmented architectures address this through external memory stores. Recent work has also explored variational framing of autoencoders with structured priors, casting sparse autoencoders as latent-variable models where ad-hoc penalties can be replaced with ELBO losses under structured priors. Mixture-based VAE extensions incorporate mixture distributions for both posterior and prior components, formulating new ELBO objectives to approximate underlying data distributions.

2.5 Continual and Self-Supervised Learning

Continual learning—the ability of a neural network to learn multiple sequential tasks without catastrophic forgetting—remains a central challenge. When a standard neural network is trained on a new task, optimization fine-tunes weights to the new data distribution, often overwriting parameters encoding prior knowledge. Recent approaches include Cluster-Aware Replay (CAR), integrating a small class-balanced replay buffer with feature-space regularization that penalizes overlapping feature representations between new and previously learned tasks.

The IntPhys 2 benchmark evaluates intuitive physics understanding of deep learning models, focusing on four core principles: Permanence, Immutability, Spatio-Temporal Continuity, and Solidity. Using the violation of expectation framework, most models perform at chance levels (50%), while humans achieve near-perfect accuracy.

2.6 Research Gaps

Existing world models lack:

1. Entity-centric evolving representations (flat latents vs. dynamic graphs),
2. Persistent long-horizon memory without quadratic cost,
3. Multimodal fusion that preserves modality-specific structure and intuitive physics,
4. Self-supervised continual learning that avoids forgetting while enabling perpetual adaptation.

No architecture simultaneously satisfies sub-100 ms latency, \ge 1000-step coherence, <20% generalization drop, and emergent intuitive physics. The proposed NWSE addresses these gaps through an RSSM backbone augmented with dynamic graph scene graphs, memory-augmented transformers, and self-supervised equivariant predictive objectives.

