3.7 Complexity Analysis

The computational complexity per timestep is summarized below.

Component Standard RSSM Transformer‑only NWSE (Proposed)
Temporal complexity O(T) O(T^2) O(T \log N_m)
Spatial complexity (per step) O(1) O(N_{\text{pixels}}) O(K^2) (where K = \#\text{objects})
Long‑term memory None O(T) O(N_m) with N_m \ll T

The NWSE achieves O(T \log N_m) by using a memory‑augmented transformer with approximate attention (e.g., Reformer or Performer with locality‑sensitive hashing), where each read operation is O(\log N_m). The graph complexity O(K^2) is acceptable because in typical scenes K \leq 50, much smaller than the number of pixels.

Real‑time feasibility. For K = 50, L = 3 GNN layers, N_m = 256, d_k = 128, D_h = 512, the total operations per step is approximately 4.2 \times 10^6, well under the capability of a modern edge GPU (e.g., NVIDIA Jetson Orin) to achieve sub‑100 ms latency.

