Appendix B: World Model Derivations

B.1 Variational Autoencoder (VAE) ELBO

Theorem B.1 (Evidence Lower Bound). For a generative model p_\theta(x, z) and variational posterior q_\phi(z \mid x),

\log p_\theta(x) \geq \mathbb{E}_{z \sim q_\phi(z|x)}[\log p_\theta(x \mid z)] - \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z \mid x) \| p(z)],

where the right-hand side is the Evidence Lower Bound (ELBO).

Proof.

\begin{aligned}
\log p_\theta(x) &= \int q_\phi(z \mid x) \log p_\theta(x) \, dz \\
&= \int q_\phi(z \mid x) \log \frac{p_\theta(x,z)}{p_\theta(z \mid x)} \, dz \\
&= \int q_\phi(z \mid x) \log \frac{p_\theta(x,z)}{q_\phi(z \mid x)} \, dz + \int q_\phi(z \mid x) \log \frac{q_\phi(z \mid x)}{p_\theta(z \mid x)} \, dz \\
&= \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi(z|x)}[\log p_\theta(x \mid z)] - \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z \mid x) \| p(z)] + \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z \mid x) \| p_\theta(z \mid x)] \\
&\geq \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi(z|x)}[\log p_\theta(x \mid z)] - \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z \mid x) \| p(z)].
\end{aligned}

The inequality follows because KL divergence is non‑negative. ∎

B.2 Recurrent State‑Space Model (RSSM) ELBO

Definition B.1 (RSSM Architecture). The RSSM (Hafner et al., 2023) consists of:

· Deterministic state: h_t = f_\phi(h_{t-1}, z_{t-1}, a_{t-1}) (GRU),
· Prior: \hat{z}_t \sim p_\phi(z_t \mid h_t),
· Posterior: z_t \sim q_\phi(z_t \mid h_t, x_t),
· Observation decoder: \hat{x}_t \sim p_\phi(x_t \mid h_t, z_t),
· Reward predictor: \hat{r}_t \sim p_\phi(r_t \mid h_t, z_t),
· Continuation predictor: \hat{c}_t \sim p_\phi(c_t \mid h_t, z_t).

Theorem B.2 (RSSM ELBO). The variational lower bound for the RSSM is

\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}(\phi) &= \sum_{t=1}^T \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi} \big[ \log p_\phi(x_t \mid h_t, z_t) + \log p_\phi(r_t \mid h_t, z_t) + \log p_\phi(c_t \mid h_t, z_t) \big] \\
&\quad - \sum_{t=1}^T \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z_t \mid h_t, x_t) \| p_\phi(z_t \mid h_t)].
\end{aligned}

Proof. The joint distribution factorizes as

p_\phi(x_{1:T}, r_{1:T}, c_{1:T}, z_{1:T}, h_{1:T}) = \prod_{t=1}^T p_\phi(x_t \mid h_t, z_t) p_\phi(r_t \mid h_t, z_t) p_\phi(c_t \mid h_t, z_t) p_\phi(z_t \mid h_t).

The variational posterior is

q_\phi(z_{1:T} \mid x_{1:T}, a_{1:T-1}) = \prod_{t=1}^T q_\phi(z_t \mid h_t, x_t).

Applying Theorem B.1 sequentially and summing over time yields the result. ∎

B.3 Free‑Bits Clipping

Definition B.2 (Free‑Bits). To prevent posterior collapse, DreamerV3 clips the KL divergence below 1 nat:

L_\text{dyn} = \max(1, \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z_t \mid h_t, x_t) \| p_\phi(z_t \mid h_t)]), \quad
L_\text{rep} = \max(1, \mathrm{KL}[q_\phi(z_t \mid h_t, x_t) \| p_\phi(z_t \mid h_t)]),

where \mathrm{sg}(\cdot) denotes the stop‑gradient operator.

Theorem B.3 (Free‑Bits Preserves ELBO). The free‑bits modification yields a valid lower bound:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{free}}(\phi) = \sum_t \mathbb{E}_q[\log p_\phi(x_t, r_t, c_t \mid h_t, z_t)] - \sum_t \max(1, \mathrm{KL}[q \| p]),

and satisfies \mathcal{L}_{\text{free}}(\phi) \leq \log p(x_{1:T}, r_{1:T}, c_{1:T}).

Proof. Since \max(1, \mathrm{KL}) \geq \mathrm{KL}, the bound is looser but remains a lower bound. The stop‑gradient ensures that the bound is still valid for optimization of \phi. ∎

B.4 Reparameterization Trick

Theorem B.4 (Reparameterization Trick). For a Gaussian latent variable z \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2), we can write z = \mu + \sigma \epsilon where \epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1). This allows gradient backpropagation through sampling.

Proof. The expectation \mathbb{E}_{z \sim q_\phi(z|x)}[f(z)] can be rewritten as \mathbb{E}_{\epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)}[f(\mu + \sigma \epsilon)]. Under mild regularity conditions, the gradient with respect to \mu and \sigma can be taken inside the expectation, enabling unbiased gradient estimation. ∎

