Appendix C: Graph Neural Networks and Equivariance

C.1 Message Passing Neural Networks (MPNNs)

Definition C.1 (MPNN Framework). An MPNN defines per layer:

· Message: m_{uv}^{(l)} = M^{(l)}(h_u^{(l-1)}, h_v^{(l-1)}, e_{uv}),
· Aggregation: m_v^{(l)} = \sum_{u \in \mathcal{N}(v)} m_{uv}^{(l)},
· Update: h_v^{(l)} = U^{(l)}(h_v^{(l-1)}, m_v^{(l)}).

After L layers, a readout function computes graph‑level predictions.

C.2 E(n)-Equivariant Graph Neural Networks (EGNNs)

Definition C.2 (E(n)-Equivariance). A function f: \mathbb{R}^{n \times N} \to \mathbb{R}^{n \times N} is E(n)-equivariant if for any g = (\mathbf{R}, \mathbf{t}) \in E(n) (rotation + translation),

f(g \cdot \mathbf{x}) = g \cdot f(\mathbf{x}),

where g \cdot \mathbf{x} denotes the group action applied to each point.

Theorem C.1 (EGNN Update – Satorras et al., 2021). For nodes with coordinates \mathbf{x}_i \in \mathbb{R}^n and features \mathbf{h}_i, the following update is E(n)-equivariant:

\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{m}_{ij} &= \phi_e(\mathbf{h}_i, \mathbf{h}_j, \|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|^2), \\
\mathbf{h}_i' &= \phi_h(\mathbf{h}_i, \sum_{j \neq i} \mathbf{m}_{ij}), \\
\mathbf{x}_i' &= \mathbf{x}_i + \sum_{j \neq i} (\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j) \phi_x(\mathbf{m}_{ij}),
\end{aligned}

where \phi_e, \phi_h, \phi_x are MLPs.

Proof. The message \mathbf{m}_{ij} depends only on invariant quantities (distances, inner products), so it is invariant under E(n). The aggregated sum is invariant. The coordinate update uses differences \mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j which are translation‑invariant and rotate as \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j). The scalar factor \phi_x(\mathbf{m}_{ij}) is invariant, so the update is equivariant. ∎

C.3 SO(3)-Equivariant Spherical Representations

Definition C.3 (Spherical Harmonics). The spherical harmonics Y_l^m(\theta, \phi) form a basis for square‑integrable functions on S^2. Under a rotation \mathbf{R} \in SO(3),

Y_l^m(\mathbf{R}^{-1} \mathbf{r}) = \sum_{m'=-l}^l D_{m'm}^{(l)}(\mathbf{R}) Y_l^{m'}(\mathbf{r}),

where D^{(l)}(\mathbf{R}) are the Wigner D‑matrices.

Theorem C.2 (SO(3)-Equivariant Convolution – Thomas et al., 2018). The spherical convolution defined by

(f \star g)(\mathbf{R}) = \int_{SO(3)} f(\mathbf{R}') g(\mathbf{R}'^{-1} \mathbf{R}) \, d\mathbf{R}'

is SO(3)-equivariant.

Proof. Under left translation L_{Q}f(\mathbf{R}) = f(Q^{-1}\mathbf{R}), the convolution satisfies (L_Q f) \star g = L_Q(f \star g). This is a standard property of group convolutions. ∎

C.4 Equivariance and Conservation Laws

Theorem C.3 (Noether’s Theorem for Discrete Symmetries). If a neural network f is exactly SO(3)-equivariant, then for any input that satisfies a physical Lagrangian with rotational symmetry, the network’s output respects conservation of angular momentum.

Proof Sketch. Noether’s theorem states that continuous symmetries of the action imply conserved currents. For a discrete approximation (the neural network), exact equivariance ensures that the same symmetry applies to the output. The network therefore cannot create angular momentum from a rotationally symmetric input. ∎

