Appendix E: Johnson–Lindenstrauss Lemma

E.1 Statement and Proof

Theorem E.1 (Johnson–Lindenstrauss Lemma, 1984). For any \epsilon \in (0,1) and any set X of N points in \mathbb{R}^D, there exists a linear map f: \mathbb{R}^D \to \mathbb{R}^d with d = O(\epsilon^{-2} \log N) such that for all x, y \in X,

(1 - \epsilon) \|x - y\|^2 \leq \|f(x) - f(y)\|^2 \leq (1 + \epsilon) \|x - y\|^2.

Proof Sketch (Dasgupta & Gupta, 2003). Choose a random projection matrix \Pi \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times D} with i.i.d. Gaussian entries \mathcal{N}(0, 1/d). For a fixed pair (x, y), \| \Pi x - \Pi y\|^2 is a scaled \chi^2 distribution with d degrees of freedom. Using concentration inequalities,

P\left( \big| \| \Pi x - \Pi y\|^2 - \|x - y\|^2 \big| \geq \epsilon \|x - y\|^2 \right) \leq 2e^{-d(\epsilon^2/4 - \epsilon^3/6)}.

Set d = \frac{4 \log N}{\epsilon^2/2 - \epsilon^3/3}. Apply a union bound over all \binom{N}{2} pairs. ∎

E.2 Approximate Nearest Neighbor Guarantee

Theorem E.2 (ANN Guarantee). Let \mathcal{K} = \{\mathbf{k}_1, \dots, \mathbf{k}_{N_m}\} be a set of memory keys with separation constant \alpha = \min_{i \neq j} \|\mathbf{k}_i - \mathbf{k}_j\|. For any query \mathbf{q}, let \mathbf{k}^* be the true nearest neighbor and \tilde{\mathbf{k}} be the nearest neighbor in the Johnson‑Lindenstrauss projection. Then

P(\tilde{\mathbf{k}} \neq \mathbf{k}^*) \leq N_m^2 \exp\left(-\frac{\epsilon^2 \alpha^2}{8}\right).

Proof. The JL lemma ensures that for any two keys, the projected distance is within (1 \pm \epsilon) of the original distance with probability \geq 1 - 2e^{-d\epsilon^2/4}. If \|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}^*\| \leq \|\mathbf{q} - \mathbf{k}_j\| - \delta with \delta > 0, the projection preserves the ordering. The probability of failure for any pair is at most 2e^{-d\epsilon^2/4}. A union bound over all \binom{N_m}{2} pairs gives the result. ∎

