Appendix G: Self‑Supervised Predictive Coding

G.1 V‑JEPA Objective

Definition G.1 (Masked Prediction Loss – Bardes et al., 2024). Given a video sequence V_{1:T}, mask a subset of timesteps \mathcal{M}. Let V_C be the corrupted video (masked regions removed). The V‑JEPA objective is

\mathcal{L}_{\text{pred}} = \mathbb{E}_{\mathcal{M}} \left[ \sum_{t \in \mathcal{M}} \left\| \text{sg}\big( f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}}(V_{1:t}^{\text{unmasked}}) \big) - p_\phi^{\text{pred}}(\{z_{<t}^{\text{unmasked}}\}) \right\|_1 \right],

where \text{sg} denotes stop‑gradient and f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}} is an exponential moving average target network.

G.2 Surprise Metric for Intuitive Physics

Definition G.2 (Surprise). The surprise on a physically impossible video is

S_t = \left\| p_\phi^{\text{pred}}(\{z_{<t}^{\text{unmasked}}\}) - f_{\theta_{\text{EMA}}}(V_{1:t}^{\text{unmasked}}) \right\|_1.

G.3 Theoretical Guarantee for Intuitive Physics

Theorem G.1 (Emergent Physical Understanding). If the predictor p_\phi^{\text{pred}} is trained on videos satisfying physical laws (object permanence, gravity, solidity) and the training loss converges to a small value, then on held‑out violation videos the surprise S_t exceeds a threshold \tau with probability approaching 1 as the amount of training data increases.

Proof Sketch. The predictor learns the conditional distribution of future latents given the past. Physically impossible videos have low probability under the true physical distribution. By the law of large numbers, the prediction error (surprise) converges to the expected error under the true distribution, which is higher for violation videos. ∎

