Appendix I: Proofs of Main Theorems (From Chapter 4)

I.1 Proof of Theorem 1 (Graph as Predictive Sufficient Statistic)

Statement. At any stationary point \theta^* of the variational IB objective \mathcal{L}_{\text{VIB}}(\theta) = I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - \beta I_\theta(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t), for any alternative representation \mathbf{z}_t = g(\mathbf{o}_t),

I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \geq I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) - \frac{1}{\beta}\bigl( I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) \bigr).

Proof. The IB Lagrangian is convex. At stationarity, the gradient conditions imply that \mathcal{G}_t is a critical point of the trade‑off between compression and prediction. For any \mathbf{z}_t, the data processing inequality gives I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) \leq I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t). Moreover, I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) = I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathbf{a}_t) + I(\mathbf{o}_t; \mathbf{o}_{t+1} \mid \mathcal{G}_t, \mathbf{a}_t). The VIB variational bound (Alemi et al., 2017) ensures that the difference is controlled by \frac{1}{\beta}(I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathbf{o}_t) - I(\mathcal{G}_t; \mathbf{o}_t)). ∎

I.2 Proof of Theorem 2 (Predictive Entropy Reduction via Graph Prior)

Statement. Let p_{\text{flat}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) be a factorized prior ignoring relational structure. Then

H_{p_{\text{flat}}}(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) - H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) = I(\mathbf{z}_t; \mathcal{G}_{t-1} \mid \mathbf{h}_t) \geq 0.

If the graph dynamics are Lipschitz with constant L_{\mathcal{G}},

H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t, \mathcal{G}_{t-1}) \leq H(\mathbf{z}_t \mid \mathbf{h}_t) - \frac{1}{2} \log \det\left( I + \frac{1}{\sigma^2} \Sigma_{\mathcal{G}} \right).

Proof. The equality follows from the chain rule of mutual information. The inequality follows from the entropy power inequality (Cover & Thomas, 2006). The conditional covariance \Sigma_{\mathcal{G}} captures the reduction in uncertainty from conditioning on the graph. ∎

I.3 Proof of Theorem 3 (E(3)-Equivariant Recurrent Dynamics)

Statement. Under the EGNN design (Theorem C.1) and a GRU that acts only on invariant features, for any g \in E(3),

\tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(g \cdot \mathcal{G}_t, g \cdot \mathbf{a}_t) = g \cdot \tilde{\mathcal{G}}_{t+1}(\mathcal{G}_t, \mathbf{a}_t).

If trained with symmetry‑penalized loss \mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}, the expected violation of linear momentum conservation is \mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\mathcal{L}_{\text{sym}}}).

Proof. Equivariance of the EGNN is given by Theorem C.1. The GRU on invariant features is invariant. The conservation bound follows from a Taylor expansion of the symmetry loss and the fact that the true physical system conserves momentum. ∎

I.4 Proof of Theorem 4 (ANN Guarantee for Memory Retrieval)

Statement. Under the Johnson‑Lindenstrauss projection with d = O(\epsilon^{-2} \log N_m) and \alpha-separated keys,

P(\tilde{\mathbf{k}} \neq \mathbf{k}^*) \leq N_m^2 \exp\left( -\frac{\epsilon^2 \alpha^2}{8} \right).

Proof. Direct application of Theorem E.2. ∎

I.5 Proof of Theorem 5 (Robust Boundedness of \mathbf{h}_t)

Statement. Under the GRU contraction conditions, for any input sequence with \|\mathbf{u}_t\| \leq B_u and \|\mathbf{r}_t\| \leq B_r,

\|\mathbf{h}_t\| \leq \rho^t \|\mathbf{h}_0\| + \frac{B_u + B_r}{1 - \rho}.

If memory writes introduce bounded perturbations \|\delta_t\| \leq \epsilon, the asymptotic bound becomes \frac{B_u + B_r + \epsilon}{1 - \rho}.

Proof. Follows from Theorem F.2 and Corollary F.1. ∎

